Barker and Wright then expand one of these incidents -- Cutting tomato -- into fifteen more detailed action-descriptions. How information processing models of today should approach material exhibiting such volatility is far from clear.  The orderliness of thought analyzed by Anzai and Simon (their subject was a liberal arts college graduate) is not characteristic of the less regular thought of the child from whom every adult develops.

^^^^^^^^^^With 49 children as subjects, the explicit models of Klahr and Robinson (1981), like the production systems of Anzai and Simon, describe various strategies for solving the Towers of Hanoi puzzle (in a three disk variation). Each child was exposed to the problem for 45 minutes or less over a few consecutive days.  Klahr and Robinson focussed on states of knowledge and specifically deferred any studies of learning, i.e. state transitions, to later work.  By working with many children, they avoid describing idiosyncratic behavior, a criticism to which my work and that of Anzai and Simon is vulnerable. (But see the arguments of Lewin on this specific issue.)  The short sessions, focussed by a teacher-experimenter, helped to contain the childrens' volatility and the centrifugal forces of individual's differing interests.  The price Klahr and Robinson have paid is greater complexity in aggregating their data and in attempting to show its significance.  My reason for contrasting the work of Klahr and Robinson to that of Anzai and Simon and of Barker and Wright is to emphasize that for approaching the significant issue of how the problem solving and learning of the adult emerges from that of the child, a different sort of study is important, one on a scale long enough for significant excursions of thought to appear and also detailed enough, where it matters, to permit at least a sketch of what is really going on.  I attempted such a sketch in "The Progressive Construction of Mind," one focussed on how controlled and controllable thought might develop from disparate and competing cognitive structures.  Here I attempt to address an issue of comparable scope, how the thought of another becomes possible to imagine with the cognitive structures of the self.

^^^^^^^^^^Agreeing that around age six children first become capable of putting themselves in others' roles, scientists of various paradigms have raised the issue of how another becomes a part of the self; each has provided a characteristic vision.  Freud, for example, proposed that the other within the self derives from the introjection of parents.  I offer an information processing perspective, in the broad sense, on that question: the ability to imagine the thought of another develops from the splitting apart and subordinating of alternative structures within the self; further, whatever the cause may be for such a development, we can trace it in experiences with problem domains whose particular structure permits essentially different sorts of problem solving activities to proceed.

^^^^^^^^^^The Intimate Study has taken a course between the analysis of limited scope experimental protocols and the overwhelming detail of a complete ecological study in the fashion of Barker and Wright.  By tracing the development of knowledge about topics sufficiently interesting to Miriam that she returned to them over a long period of time, I have explored the learning of a single mind on its natural scale of development -- that of months and years -- while still preserving a sufficiency of material for detailed analysis where the pattern of development indicates the effort is justified.  I invite my colleagues whose forte is precise modelling to extend such preliminaries as I propose here to more explicit models that can capture the subtilty and power of the cognitive processes witnessed in this analysis.  The Intimate Study was inspired in part by a suggestion of Flavell's (1963).  In a discussion of the stability of Piagetian stages, he proposed a blending of Piaget's focus on cognitive structures with the ecological emphasis of Barker and Wright, "a type of research endeavor which has not yet been exploited: an ecological study of the young child's mundane interchanges with his workaday world."  With this inspiration, The Intimate Study draws support from Flavell's subsequent conclusion "in view of the infertility of most training methods so far tried, no source of new ideas ought to be ignored."  (I do not believe the phenomena of learning have been definitively explained in the years since Flavell's comment.  See Norman, 1980.)

Cognitive Structures^^^^^^^^^^This article does not present explicit cognitive models, but some of its ideas bear on cognitive modelling and in particular on the explanation of stages.  Attempting to explain saltations in performance as deriving from small but significant changes in cognitive structures is not a novelty.  Piaget's (1947) theory of subsuming stages is itself an early example of such an attempt.  Papert's explanations of conservation development through control structure change (proposed early in the 70's or before, now reflected in Papert, 1980), my own interpretations (Lawler, 1979, 1981) and others (e.g. Simon, 1975; Case, 1978) show the attempt to explain noteworthy changes in behavior as deriving from small changes in the flow of control to various mental structures.  The significant distinction to make among these efforts is how the bootstrapping of cognitive structure -- the elevation of control I call it -- takes place.  Piaget imagined that the elevation of control derived from the perfection of homogeneous layers of cognitive structures.  Case (1978), influenced by Simon and others, bases his position on limitations of cognitive loading.  He argues that a progressive "automaticity" of strategies reduces their functional demands on a limited resource (STM -- short term memory) and this permits, in turn, an increment of control over such strategies, from which emerge significant changes in behavior.  In contrast,  my earlier explanations, applying and extending Papert's idea of the creation of supervisory agents, are more local than global and present a somewhat "sterilized" Freudian vision, as the following.  Starting from the premise that experience must be much compartmentalized to be understandable, we imagine cognitive structures develop in response to solving problems in a variety of specific settings.  If we assume moreover that cognitive structures are active and compete to apply themselves to problems encountered, that competition surely creates a potential for confusion that must be controlled.  For example, on the same three-by-three cardboard grid we occasionally used for playing Tic^tac^toe, I introduced Miriam to Hexapawn, a pawn capture game.  Miriam ably controlled any potential confusion between the two games, but the relatedness of the two in her mind became evident in a "joke" she played in one specific Tic^tac^toe game: when I moved in a cell she wanted to occupy, Miriam performed a diagonal pawn-capture of my Tic^tac^toe marker to take that cell.  The suppression of confusion between disparate, competing cognitive structures, by limiting that competition, implies the existence of "must--not-confound" links between those disparate structures.  In "The Progressive Construction of Mind" (Lawler, 1981), I propose that the accidental agreement of competing outputs (where none should be expected) is a significant cognitive event which converts a negative link (inhibiting competition) into a postitive (but most vague) relational link.  Here, we further extend this latter sort of explanation -- where a site of inhibition becomes a locus of control element insertion -- to a different type of structure: the turn taking issues in play (which if not respected interrupt the game) may be seen initially as sites for interrupting the flow of information; later those same sites can serve for the insertion of new control elements whose exercise can radically change the capability of the structure they subordinate.  

^^^^^^^^^^^In "The Progressive Construction of Mind" (Lawler, 1981), I described Miriam's arithmetic learning in terms of microworlds -- information structures with which I proposed to represent her cognitive structures.  This paper does not explore further the internal structure of microworlds, because the nature of the observational material does not permit doing so.  If my descriptions were more precise, they would be less accurate.  Consequently, the summarizing diagrams to be encountered in this paper will contain many "empty circles" representing microworlds. For the sake of those readers who -- like myself -- feel uneasy when they see such diagrams,  I consider myself obliged to describe how I conceive of what might be inside a microworld.  I do so in appendix II.    Although it does not permit justifying such an internal structure as is presented in that appendix, the empirical corpus does permit us to ask and to answer such questions as: "What microworlds should we ascribe to Miriam ?" and "How does the control structure of interworld organization develop^?"

^^^^^^^^^^After we trace developing inter-world control structure through the interpretation of the corpus, we will discuss the relation of changes in that control structure to the appearance of stage-like changes in modes of behavior.  To avoid arguments about stage theory peripheral to the focus of this article, I will adopt the more neutral and vague term PHASE to label mutually exclusive periods of time with significant commonality in modes of play and imputed comprehension.  Based on her answers to such predictive questions as  "Have you won this game already^?", we will conclude that Miriam's knowledge of necessary relations between pattern and serial aspects of the game progressed from the first to the third of the four phases of comprehension described below:
