An Initial Sketch^^^^^^^^^^On the basis of this characterization of her initial play and thought, let us ascribe microworlds to Miriam covering the main points of the verbal description.  Figure^1 is a sketch of the Tic^tac^toe microworlds I ascribe to Miriam at the beginning of The Intimate Study.  Because we can clearly identify the incident through which strategic play first entered Miriam's Tic^tac^toe repertoire, we can confidently assert that her play was of two major kinds, strategic and what I call "tactical", implying by this latter term a shorter planning scope.  More simply put, strategic play has a game length objective; tactical play only focusses on one move at a time.  Once she learned about the three corner fork -- the knowledge effecting which is the content of the CORNERS microworld -- Miriam's failure to win and block the threat  of game 1.5 argue that when the Corners world was active in a specific game, tactical play did not operate.  Further, note that achieving the Corners fork does not require tactical play.  That is, strategic and tactical are alternate modes of play.  Miriam regularly preferred strategic to tactical play.  Nonetheless after the beginning of strategic play, Miriam's tactical play remained operative, functioning in a default capacity when she did not move first (and thus could not get enough corners for her fork) or when she consciously avoided the only strategy she knew.  In Figure^1, however, I ascribe to Miriam not one tactical microworld but a cluster of three competing microworlds.  WIN recognizes ways to win in any orientation.   BLOCK recognizes opponent's threats.  POSITION directs the next move preferentially to the center, a corner cell, or a side cell when neither an immediate win nor a threat is recognized.    Later observational material (in the upcoming section "Forced Moves") supports the ascription.  Before presenting that material I can mention two points which bear on the triple-world ascription, albeit in a permissive more than a constraining way.   First, there is not a detailed record of behavior before the advent of strategic play; therefore the corpus does not permit us to justify either the one-world or three-world ascription. Further, at the level of performance, it doesn't really matter much whether there is a single tactcal microworld or a cluster of three.  Although the microworlds might be competitively organized, the facts of how the moves of the game develop prevent the microworlds from coming into regular competition except in mid-game moves.  (One has no opportunity to win a game until the third move nor any need to block a threat until the second, at the earliest; after four moves, significant choice of positions is limited severely by the cells already occupied.)
				
^^^^^^^^^^Even a rough sketch should respect the need for a system of such structures to function in playing the game.  They should be able to propose a reasonable move at any time and to inhibit moves at the "wrong" time, i.e. one should not move out of turn but should respect the basic rules of play. The flow of information follows an "input/output" cycle; because we assume microworlds are fundamentally active, we describe this as an ACQUISITION/PROPOSITION cycle.  Somehow is presented QUERY, a question, "What move next^?", and information (the markers already in place in the external grid).  Upon acquisition of input, the microworlds propose moves.  Miriam did not attempt to make every move she thought of, only those possible in  her turn.  The game issues represent such contextual control as the rules of the game require.  For example, within each game, one must not play in the opponent's turn.  Further, one must decide who should move first in a given game.  Miriam's play showed numerous times that she was inclined to move out-of-turn, knew what specific move she would make if it were her turn.  She inhibited her action, not her thought.  I show the impact of these issues on play as inhibitions of microworld output.  One major issue is "how to play this turn^?"  A second set of issues, quasi-contractual, address the question of whether or not one should be playing Tic^tac^toe at all.  For Miriam at the age of six, her criterion of a fair game contract was that she be allowed to win in her turn, which we indicate with the question, "whose turn to win a game^?"  The issues' potential for inhibiting output is indicated by a normally-closed switch on the output data path.  (Think of these switches as opening only during the output phase of the move cycle.)  Similarly, the preference for strategic over tactical play is shown by the output of the Corners world inhibiting the output of the tactical cluster.

