/^/On Tic^Tac^toe/Appendix I

^^^^^^^^^^Tic^tac^toe is commonly judged a trivial game, child's play, yet it is complex enough to defy the sort of elegant state-space description employed by Klahr and Robinson (1981) for describing the states of the three disk Hanoi Tower puzzle.  In that domain, there are three ways a single disk can be put on a set of three pegs and thus nine ways for two disks and twenty seven for three disks on three pegs.  In contrast, the space of possible Tic^tac^toe games is determined by a sequence of nine choices, each move excluding subsequent choices of the previously selected cell.  The size of that space is nine factorial (or 362,880) possible states of the game.  This mind-boggling multitude of possible games can, however, be organized for better comprehension by calling upon symmetry and classifying games by their first two moves.

A Pattern Oriented View^^^^^^^^^^Invariance under rotation being granted, there can be only three initial moves: middle, corner, and side.  To each of these opening moves, only a few responses are possible: to a middle opening, two ( a side cell or a corner); to a corner cell, five; to a side cell, five.  The number of "opening games" necessary to consider is twelve.  As many as seven moves remain, however, and remembering games with all those endings can loom as a computational explosion for a human mind.  One surprising fact makes it possible to imagine a simple but systematic view of Tic Tac Toe: of the twelve opening games defined by the placement of the first two markers, seven openings permit direct victory by an expert initiator.  These twelve openings, defined by the pattern of the first two markers, are set out in Figure^7.  Those opening games are extended to show typical expert play.  The five side openings are rarely encountered and can be ignored with little risk.  Of the five corner openings, four permit an expert win and the fifth permits setting of traps. If you grant the casual player's view is focussed on middle openings, the conclusion follows that a significant advantage accrues to an initiator who opens in the corner.

.ce
* * * insert Figure 7 about here * * *

^^^^^^^^^^The preceding view of the game is very much pattern oriented, in contrast with the common form of play where the next move is selected by an analysis (usually depth first) of consequent moves from the current state to game end -- what Newell and Simon (1972) call "forward play in the game tree of possibilities."  Although Miriam's play was predominantly pattern oriented (she could not play forward in the game tree more than a single opponent's move), her play did not focus on opening patterns.  It focussed on forks.  An alternative to the preceding view is necessary.  Let us define some terms.  A WAY TO WIN is any row of three cells with two like markers in it, the third cell being empty.  A FORK is a marker-connected intersection of two such ways to win.  The strategic power derives from making that intersection by placing a LINK at the intersection of two rows which had been merely CHANCES TO WIN.  (Such is a row of three cells, two empty.)  Placing the link creates two ways to win with one move.  The opponent can only block one, and thus the forking player is assured of victory. The specification of forks as patterns both of markers and holes delimits precisely the opponent's moves which may frustrate a fork.  This emphasizes the role of the initiator's second move as crucial: this move must appear as a marker in the fork; it must force the opponent's second move to a non-interfering cell, preventing it from impeding the placement of the link.  Below, game (b) fails because this crucial move (which we name the CRUX) permits  the opponent to establish a way to win which must immediately be blocked:
