^^^^^^^^^The opening-oriented view gains power from a surprising fact, the extent to which expert wins permit simplifying one's thinking about Tic tac toe, and is useful because it gives effective guidance in play.  In contrast, the fork-oriented view goes a long way to explaining the "surprising fact" that renders the opening-oriented view effective.  Thinking in fork oriented terms may be too difficult for a novice in actual competition, but it may be well suited for a person puzzling over past games or playing them against herself.  The essential complementarity is that both point to the crux, the initiator's second move, as the critical bridge between opening and fork.

Remote Connections^^^^^^^^^^My analysis of Tic tac toe seems similar in kind to that of Michael Clarke's two chess endgames described in Berliner's review of the Artificial Intelligence chess literature (1978) and characterized as developing "a database of perfect information."  When translated into computer based game play, Miriam's  stage change would be equivalent to the transformation of a pattern-oriented learning game player -- such as BOGART (Newman & Uhr, 1965) -- into a system which could play by forward search in the game tree (Cf. the discussion by Newell and Simon, 1972, p.665 ff., of the chess task environment).  Such a system, even after developing a forward search capablity, might remain largely pattern-oriented and might be expected to tend toward pattern-oriented systematic formulations, such as that of Figure^7.  The equivalent to a procedural-to-systematic transformation, however, would be at best only locally possible, given the enormous complexity of chess.  It might be possible for an intelligence with broad experience of such a complex game to develop nodes of locally systematic knowledge, which whenever the boundary conditions of such determined knowledge mated would produced surprisingly powerful play.  Newell and Simon's discussion (1972, p.780) of de Groot's results do not prohibit such an interpretation of the play of chess masters. 
