/^/Microworlds/Appendix II

^^^^^^^^^^"Microworld" is a term with a history in the A.I. community.  It was used by Minsky and Papert (1974) to refer both to environments beyond the person and to structures within the mind.  In this place, I restrict my use of the term to the latter sense.   MICROWORLDS are active descriptions, competitively organized.  Each microworld recognizes the problem situations to which it might apply and then acts upon that recognition.  One part of a microworld, the PERSPECTIVE, analyzes a problem into its significant parts.  (This is the recognition process.  Think of the perspective as a collection of demon procedures which assign values to their unfilled slots upon partial matching of invocation patterns individually.)  The perspective of a microworld determines "what's what" from its viewpoint.  The matching of some available input to the patterns of perspective elements activates related FUNCTIONS, the second major microworld component, which propose a solution to the problem.  (Think of this process as an activation cascade within a network of subsidiary demon procedures.  In terms of a network description, the nodes of a microworld would be processes computing values for as yet unspecified slots (which would be sent as messages along links to other nodes) from the values whose specification activated them initially. 

^^^^^^^^^^The typical situation to which a microworld applies is one of solving some simple problem, e.g. 2^+^?^=^4.  Solutions derive from the intersections of the net.  They return an "output" as a perspective element (either filling a slot not determined by the problem presentation or competing with such a one).  Functions may be thought of as deductions, "what^follows" from "what's^what".  A simple problem presented to a Tic tac toe microworld might be "What move next^?", given input information about the state of the game.  The perspective elements of a Tic^tac^toe microworld would be filled by demon procedures which note the presence and ownership of a mark in a cell.  Compared to the microworlds of arithmetic, the microworlds of Tic tac toe experience are simple because the game is representationally shallow -- as the hindu-arabic notation with its subtilty of "place value" is not -- and because the varieties of Tic tac toe experience are very limited.

A question of balance^^^^^^^^^^In the final comments of their discussion, Klahr and Robinson (1981) call for a different balance in the analysis of problem solving development, one where the issue of the subject's encoding of the problem will receive as much prominence as which strategies are used.  That call echoes a theme in The Origins of Scientific Reasoning (Siegler, 1978), that what children are able to recognize as potentially significant in a problem is a primary determinant of what problems they will be able to learn to solve.   I paraphrase this concern as one of establishing the proper  balance between recognizing "what's what" and deducing "what follows."  Because I tend to believe that the chains of inference possible without confusion are very short, my description of the mind as microworlds leans heavily to a recognition-side preponderance, as in this extreme slogan: "what follows from what's what is either intuitively obvious or else unthinkable."  The issue of recognition/deduction balance in the mind brings to the fore a second important question, one bearing on the cognitive modelling of a human mind which typically may be broad and relatively shallow.  Those of us who have been in the computer cultures of the last twenty years have a deep experience of directed invocation and of the power and complexity of serial executive structures.  Our experience of the complexity of interacting parallel structures and of the ways in which order can emerge from such systems is relatively shallow; this may limit our imagination.  Even if current formalisms are adequate, our imaginations may be too much committed to our concrete experience of serial systems I expect the precise formulation of information processing models committed to broad but shallow cognitive structures to follow the development of software systems for the extensive application and optimizing of parallel computer systems.  

Predictions about Learning^^^^^^^^^^A proposal, even an admittedly imprecise one, which pretends to theoretical significance should address, as best it can, the question of what consequences its truth might have.  The idea of competing microworlds, coupled with a definitional idea, permits us to begin predicting that some things should be essentially harder to learn than others.  Compare the two expert victories for the C2 opening game below:
