Game (b) is harder to learn than game (a).  We have two bits of evidence: Miriam discovered (a) but not (b); I discovered (a) first, then chose (b) for  systematic recall because it permitted unifying the crux move to cell 7 for all corner expert wins.  Why should (b) be harder than (a)^?  And what does it mean, precisely, for one problem to be harder than another^?  The distinction can be made precise by applying Kohler's criterion (1925) for the existence of intelligence; i.e. intelligence is shown only when the circumstances having blocked a problem's direct solution, the creature must take a roundabout path.  We assume it is "hard" to act intelligently.  If we judge  a player's move which avoids the middle cell to be a "detour" (because of a strong Tactical preference for a center move), any strategic gambit which requires keeping the middle empty at a particular move will be "harder" than a strategy which calls for moving to the middle cell at that same move.  We assume such a game is harder because it requires suppression of the competing proposals from the tactical microworlds.   By such reasoning, the C2 victory of Figure^7 (b above), is "harder" than the C2 victory of Miriam's new strategy (a above).  Similarly, the C1 game of Figure^7 is "hardest" of all corner opening games because it requires the middle cell remain empty through placement of the link.
